This use case could use a multiline regex ont the entire text, but in general is not suited.

For instance also considering a string literal `&quot;//&quot;` would make it really unwise (need to find pairs). And with the latest java there are multi line literals.

Regex on the entire text of multiple lines using `(?s)` to interprete `.` also as wildcard for line breaks:

    Pattern comment = Pattern.compile(&quot;(?s)(/\\*.*?\\*/|//.*?\\R)&quot;); // Or
    Pattern comment = Pattern.compile(&quot;(/\\*.*?\\*/|//.*?\\R)&quot;, Pattern.MULTILINE);
                                        ----------- --------
                                        /* ...   */ // ...
    comment.matcher(text). ...



Coded out is simpler. Here for returning only the real code lines:

    Stream&lt;String&gt; uncommentedLines(Stream&lt;String&gt; lines) {
        AtomicBoolean insideBlockComment = new AtomicBoolean();
        return lines.flatMap(line -&gt; {
            if (insideBlockComment.get()) {
                int p = line.indexOf(&quot;*/&quot;);
                if (p != -1) {
                    insideBlockComment.set(false);
                    return line.substring(p + 2);
                }
                return Stream.empty();
            } else {
                int p = line.indexOf(&quot;//&quot;);
                if (p != -1) {
                    line = line.substring(0, p);
                }
                p = line.indexOf(&quot;/*&quot;);
                if (p != -1) {
                    insideBlockComment.set(true);
                    line = line.substring(0, p);
                }
                return Stream.of(line);
            }
        });
    }

One usage for regex is to undo u-escaping of say `\u002F` (`&#39;/&#39;`):

    // Java &gt;= 9
    text = Pattern.compile(&quot;(?i)\\u([0-9A-Fa-F]{4})&quot;).matcher(text)
        .replaceAll(mR -&gt; Character.toString((char)Integer.parseInt(mR.group(1), 16)));

